.TH SIMPLE_SHELL 1 "April 2026" "Holberton School" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
simple_shell \- a simple UNIX command line interpreter
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B simple_shell
.br
.B simple_shell
[script_file]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B simple_shell
is a minimalist UNIX shell written in C as part of the Holberton School
curriculum. It reads commands from standard input (interactive or piped),
resolves their paths through the
.B PATH
environment variable, and executes them using
.BR execve (2).
.PP
The shell supports two built-in commands and external command execution.
It handles both interactive and non-interactive modes automatically by
testing whether standard input is a terminal with
.BR isatty (3).
.SH INVOCATION
When invoked interactively (standard input connected to a terminal), the
shell displays the prompt
.B $
before each command. When standard input is not a terminal (pipe or file
redirection), no prompt is printed and the shell reads commands silently
until EOF.
.PP
The shell exits when it reads EOF (Ctrl+D in interactive mode) or when the
.B exit
built-in is called.
.SH COMMAND EXECUTION
For each line of input, the shell:
.IP 1. 4
Reads the line with
.BR getline (3)
and trims leading and trailing whitespace (spaces and tabs).
.IP 2. 4
Splits the trimmed line into tokens using spaces and tabs as delimiters
(via
.BR split_string ).
.IP 3. 4
Checks whether the first token matches a built-in command
.RB ( exit ", " env ).
.IP 4. 4
If not a built-in, resolves the full executable path via
.BR pathfinder ,
which searches each directory listed in the
.B PATH
environment variable. If the command string contains a
.B /
character, it is used directly (after checking execute permission via
.BR stat (2)).
.IP 5. 4
Forks a child process with
.BR fork (2),
executes the command with
.BR execve (2)
and
.BR environ ,
and waits for completion with
.BR waitpid (2).
.IP 6. 4
Returns the exit status of the child to the shell loop.
.PP
Empty lines and lines consisting only of whitespace are silently ignored.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.B simple_shell
inherits the calling process's environment via the global
.B extern char **environ
variable. The built-in
.B env
command prints all variables in this array, one per line.
.PP
The shell reads
.B PATH
to locate external executables. If
.B PATH
is unset or empty, only commands specified with an explicit path will be found.
.SH EXIT STATUS
The shell exits with the exit status of the last command it executed.
.PP
.TP
.B 0
Successful execution.
.TP
.B 1
A
.BR fork (2)
failure occurred.
.TP
.B 127
Command not found: the executable could not be located in
.B PATH
or at the given path.
.PP
Any other value reflects the exit status returned by the last child process,
extracted with
.BR WEXITSTATUS (3).
.SH SYNTAX
Commands follow this simple syntax:
.PP
.RS
.I command
[argument ...]
.RE
.PP
Tokens are separated by one or more spaces or tab characters. No quoting,
no escaping, no variable expansion, no glob expansion, and no command
substitution are supported.
.SH ERROR HANDLING
When a command is not found, the shell prints to standard error:
.PP
.RS
.I prog_name: line_num: command: not found
.RE
.PP
where
.I prog_name
is
.BR argv[0] ,
.I line_num
is the 1-based index of the command in the current session, and
.I command
is the unresolved token.
.PP
When
.BR fork (2)
fails,
.BR perror (3)
is called and the shell returns status 1.
.PP
When
.BR execve (2)
fails inside the child, the same
.I "not found"
message is printed to standard error, memory is freed, and the child exits
with status 127 via
.BR _exit (2).
.SH SYSTEM CALLS AND LIBRARY FUNCTIONS
.SS System calls
.TP
.BR fork (2)
Creates a child process for each external command.
.TP
.BR execve (2)
Replaces the child's image with the target executable, passing
.B environ
as the environment.
.TP
.BR waitpid (2)
Waits for the child to terminate and collects its exit status.
.TP
.BR write (2)
Outputs the interactive prompt and the lines printed by the
.B env
built-in.
.TP
.BR _exit (2)
Terminates the child immediately after a failed
.BR execve (2).
.TP
.BR stat (2)
Checks whether a candidate path is executable (
.B S_IXUSR
flag) during PATH resolution.
.TP
.BR isatty (3)
Detects whether standard input is a terminal to decide whether to print the
prompt.
.SS Library functions
.TP
.BR getline (3)
Reads a full line from standard input, allocating memory dynamically.
.TP
.BR strtok (3)
Tokenises strings in
.B split_string
and
.BR pathfinder .
.TP
.BR malloc (3) / free (3)
Used throughout for dynamic memory allocation and release.
.TP
.BR fprintf (3) / perror (3)
Used for error reporting to standard error.
.TP
.BR sprintf (3)
Constructs candidate full paths during PATH resolution.
.TP
.BR strlen (3) / strncmp (3) / strchr (3)
Used in
.B _getenv
and
.B pathfinder
for string operations.
.TP
.BR memcpy (3)
Used in
.B split_string
to duplicate the input string before tokenising.
.SH MEMORY MANAGEMENT
All dynamically allocated memory is freed before each command cycle returns:
.IP \(bu 4
.B read_line
allocates a buffer via
.BR getline (3);
the caller (
.BR run_shell )
frees it at the end of each iteration.
.IP \(bu 4
.B split_string
allocates a working copy of the input and the resulting token array; both
are freed by
.B free_exec
after the command completes.
.IP \(bu 4
.B pathfinder
allocates a duplicate of the
.B PATH
value and the final full-path string; the full-path string is freed by
.BR free_exec ,
and the PATH copy is freed internally before the function returns.
.PP
On a failed
.BR execve (2),
the child frees its own copies via
.B free_exec
and
.BR free (3)
before calling
.BR _exit (2)
to avoid leaking memory in the child address space.
.SH LIMITATIONS
.IP \(bu 4
No pipe support
.RB ( | ).
.IP \(bu 4
No I/O redirection
.RB ( > ", " < ", " >> ).
.IP \(bu 4
No command chaining with
.B ;
or logical operators
.RB ( && ", " || ).
.IP \(bu 4
No command history or line editing.
.IP \(bu 4
No wildcard or glob expansion.
.IP \(bu 4
No variable expansion or assignment.
.IP \(bu 4
No quoting or escape character support (a space always splits tokens).
.IP \(bu 4
The
.B exit
built-in always exits with the last command's status; a numeric argument to
.B exit
is not parsed.
.IP \(bu 4
PATH resolution uses
.B strtok
internally, which is not re-entrant; nested calls would be unsafe.
.SH FILES
.TP
.B simple_shell.c
Entry point; contains
.BR main .
.TP
.B shell_loop.c
Main shell loop; contains
.BR run_shell .
.TP
.B helpers.c
Input reading and command dispatch; contains
.BR read_line ,
.BR exec_cmd ,
and the static helper
.BR run_external .
.TP
.B builtins.c
Built-in command handlers; contains
.BR handle_exit
and
.BR handle_env .
.TP
.B PATH.c
Environment and path resolution; contains
.BR _getenv
and
.BR pathfinder .
.TP
.B string_spliter.c
Tokeniser; contains
.BR split_string .
.TP
.B myfunctions.c
String utility library; contains
.BR free_exec ,
.BR _strlen ,
.BR _strdup ,
.BR _strcat_new ,
and
.BR _strcmp .
.TP
.B simple_shell.h
Single header declaring all prototypes and including system headers.
.SH COMPILATION
.nf
gcc \-Wall \-Werror \-Wextra \-pedantic \-std=gnu89 \\
    simple_shell.c shell_loop.c helpers.c builtins.c \\
    PATH.c string_spliter.c myfunctions.c \-o hsh
.fi
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Interactive mode
.nf
$ ./hsh
$ /bin/ls
AUTHORS  PATH.c  builtins.c  helpers.c  man_1_simple_shell  \\
myfunctions.c  shell_loop.c  simple_shell.c  simple_shell.h  \\
string_spliter.c
$ env
PATH=/usr/local/sbin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/sbin:/usr/bin:/sbin:/bin
HOME=/root
...
$ exit
.fi
.SS Non-interactive mode
.nf
$ echo "/bin/ls" | ./hsh
AUTHORS  PATH.c  builtins.c  helpers.c  ...
.fi
.SS Command not found
.nf
$ ./hsh
$ foobar
./hsh: 1: foobar: not found
.fi
